Name: ACOOL
Title: Air Cooling System Efficiency: Low efficiency, temperature over threshold
Description: Air Cooling System Efficiency: Low efficiency, temperature over threshold | ACOOL | Intercooler

Extra.OBDCode:
P2181-00

Cooling System Performance

No Sub Type Information
Extra.GeneralRemark: Air Intake over temperature is monitored
Extra.TestCondition:
Monitoring is active If ECU initialized since at least 6.00s while engine isn't running yet, While Engine is not in cranking mode, 6.00s after startup if engine is running, If battery voltage > 10.00V and While none of the CAN controllers is in bus-off state since at least 1000.00ms

- Monitor not inhibited (FId_ACOOLEn is intact)
- Monitor not inhibited (FId_DSR72 is intact)
- Engine is running
Extra.FaultDetection: If Air Temperature > Threshold temperature defined in a map engine speed and volumetric efficiency dependant

Name: AIR2H
Title: Air Mass Quantity estimation: Air Quantity Exceeds Desired Limit
Description: Air Mass Quantity estimation: Air Quantity Exceeds Desired Limit | AIR2H | Air flow metering

Extra.OBDCode:
P2279-00

Intake Air System Leak

No Sub Type Information
Extra.GeneralRemark: It is checked if the measured air quantity exceeds the desired one.
Extra.TestCondition:
- Monitor not inhibited by another error (FId_AIR2HEn is intact)
- engine is running
- not in cutoff mode
- Injection quantity > 0
- Engine speed > 400.00rpm
- Battery voltage > 20.00V
- Air temperature > 20.00°C
- Coolant temperature > 40.00°C
Extra.FaultDetection:
If measured air > Air target + deviation an event counter is incremented, if deviation is in range counter is decremented.

If counter exceeds 40.00adm fault is set

Extra.OBDCode:
U0046-88

Vehicle Communication Bus C

Bus off
Extra.GeneralRemark:
The proper functioning of CAN Bus is monitored. If Bus Off state at CAN controller Node 2 occurs failure is detected.

There are 3 states for the CAN node namely "error active", "error passive" and "busoff".

When the CAN controller detects that there are no CAN nodes connected, then it goes to the state "error passive". If the CAN controller detects that a CAN cable is reconnected or a new node is added, then it will go back to state "error active". If CAN node is shorted or produces only erroneous information, the state changes to busoff.

Node 2 indicates Engine CAN (ELDOR) at 500kps (CAN3)
Extra.TestCondition: Monitoring is active If ECU initialized since at least 6.00s while engine isn't running yet, While Engine is not in cranking mode, 6.00s after startup if engine is running, If battery voltage > 10.00V, If battery voltage > 10.00V since at least 2.00s, If ECU is not in afterrun, If Terminal 15 is ON and If engine speed > 150.00rpm

Name: DFLL_GAIN_ERR
Title: Lean Air Fuel Mixture Error: lean mixture due to gain drift (closed loop control variation)
Description: Lean Air Fuel Mixture Error: lean mixture due to gain drift (closed loop control variation) | DFLL_GAIN_ERR | Fuel pressure control Metering unit

Extra.OBDCode:
P0171-01

System Too Lean Bank 1

General Electrical Failure
Extra.GeneralRemark:
FuelSystem Diagnosis Function has the task of detecting malfunctions of Fuel Line System components (LNG reducer, rail, rail pressure sensor, injectors and pipes). The faults is detected when a rich or lean Air-Fuel mixture ratio occurs without correlated request from software control strategy.

Fuel Injection strategy is continuously optimized through a close loop control to maintain stoichiometric air/fuel ratio. If closed loop correction variation toward lean or rich exceeds a threshold a gain error is determined.
Extra.TestCondition:
- Monitor not inhibited (FId_DfllGainErrEn is intact)
- Monitor not inhibited (FId_DSR60 is intact)
- Boost pressure between 400.00mbar and 1400.00mbar
- Engine speed between 1100.00rpm 2700.00rpm
- Coolant temperature > 70.00°C
Extra.FaultDetection:
Closed loop correction variation is monitored.
If excessive closed loop correction variation to compensate lean mixture and maintain stoichiometric target is detected failure is issued

Description: Ignition Coil Cylinder 1: Short Circuit to Battery error | EisbCoil1SCB | Engine Coils

Extra.OBDCode:
P0351-12

Ignition Coil "A" Primary Control Circuit/Open

Circuit Short To Battery
Extra.GeneralRemark:
CAN message IONMOT6 from ELDOR contains information about misfire, knocking and coil faults for every cylinder, reported in geometric order

The message parameter IgnFaultCylFiring for cylinder X in firing order is analyzed and reported by ECU with correct fault
0== No fault
1== Open circuit error
2== Short circuit to ground error
4== Short circuit to battery error
6== Spark angular delay from coil command start too high
7== Input coil fault
8== Spark time delay from coil command stopt too hig
16== unexpected spark error
Extra.TestCondition:
Monitoring is active If ECU initialized since at least 6.00s while engine isn't running yet, While Engine is not in cranking mode, 6.00s after startup if engine is running, If battery voltage > 10.00V, If battery voltage > 10.00V since at least 2.00s, If ECU is not in afterrun, If Terminal 15 is ON, While Monitor not inhibited by another failure ( Fid_ComCILAddCond2 is intact) and If engine speed > 150.00rpm

Monitor not inhibited (FId_EisbCoil1STBEn is intact)
Extra.FaultDetection: ELDOR reports Short Circuit to Battery error for coil of Cylinder 1 (csEISBIgnFault1 == 4)

The ECM comprises so-called redundant shut-off paths  which deactivate all power stages relevant to injection if certain internal ECU errors are detected.

Name: MoFESpd
Title: ECU Internal: Diagnostic fault check to report the engine speed error
Description: ECU Internal: Diagnostic fault check to report the engine speed error | MoFESpd | ECU Internal

Extra.OBDCode:
P0607-64

Control Module Performance

Signal Plausibility Failure
Extra.GeneralRemark:
A redundant check for engine speed is performed for function monitoring at software level 2.

Monitoring in the ECM takes place in 3 levels:
Level 1: Functions level (engine control, component monitoring)
Level 2: Function monitoring level (detects defective  processes of functions in level 1)
Level 3: Controller monitoring level (check corrects processing of ECM program commands)
Extra.TestCondition: Engine speed > 1000.001/min
Extra.FaultDetection:
Either the difference between the calculated engine speed from level 1 and engine speed from level 2 is greater
than the threshold 400.001/min or there is a debounce signal error

Name: MoFVarPostBldSel
Title: ECU Internal: Post build selectable monitoring
Description: ECU Internal: Post build selectable monitoring | MoFVarPostBldSel | ECU Internal

Extra.OBDCode:
P0607-64

Control Module Performance

Signal Plausibility Failure
Extra.GeneralRemark: This function monitors the post−build selectable configuration of the basis softwar (BSW).) The BSW forwards the post−build selectable configuration to this function, which is then monitored for stability during the whole driving cycle by this function. Furthermore the safety−relevant BSW modules calculate checksums over the respectively used pointers inside of their module and return back the result to this function. In case of an error an error reaction is triggered by this function.
Extra.TestCondition: Continuously
Extra.FaultDetection:
As soon as one of the plausibility checks detects an error, which cannot be healed by a calibrateable number of resets the error flag MoFTrqPtd_flgIrrvErrPostBldSelMsg is set
and thereby the DFC is triggered

Description: ECU Internal: Safety Management Unit Alarm Group 0 Failure 1 issued | MOXEMM_SMU_ALM0_1 | ECU Internal

Extra.OBDCode:
P060C-96

Internal Control Module Main Processor Performance

Component Internal Failure
Extra.GeneralRemark:
The module MoXEMM for IFX controller makes a diagnoses of the EMM (Error Management Module) alarms, which are reported by the hardware unit SMU (Safety Management Unit).
The hardware unit SMU is a central component of the hardware safety architecture to manage the behavior of the microcontroller under the presence of hardware faults. The SMU centralizes all the alarm signals related to the different hardware and software−based safety mechanisms.
The SMU unit contains different alarm groups of which the status of each alarm is stored in corresponding status registes. The software modul MoCEMM collects cyclically the context of this status registers and provides these information to MoXEMM.
Extra.TestCondition: Continuously
Extra.FaultDetection: Safety Management Unit (SMU), Alarm Group 0 Failure 1 issued

Component Internal Failure
Extra.GeneralRemark:
The module MoXEMM for IFX controller makes a diagnoses of the EMM (Error Management Module) alarms, which are reported by the hardware unit SMU (Safety Management Unit).
The hardware unit SMU is a central component of the hardware safety architecture to manage the behavior of the microcontroller under the presence of hardware faults. The SMU centralizes all the alarm signals related to the different hardware and software−based safety mechanisms.
The SMU unit contains different alarm groups of which the status of each alarm is stored in corresponding status registes. The software modul MoCEMM collects cyclically the context of this status registers and provides these information to MoXEMM.

Component Internal Failure
Extra.GeneralRemark:
The module MoXEMM for IFX controller makes a diagnoses of the EMM (Error Management Module) alarms, which are reported by the hardware unit SMU (Safety Management Unit).
The hardware unit SMU is a central component of the hardware safety architecture to manage the behavior of the microcontroller under the presence of hardware faults. The SMU centralizes all the alarm signals related to the different hardware and software−based safety mechanisms.
The SMU unit contains different alarm groups of which the status of each alarm is stored in corresponding status registes. The software modul MoCEMM collects cyclically the context of this status registers and provides these information to MoXEMM.

Description: ECU Internal: Safety Management Unit Alarm Group 4 Failure 9 issued | MOXEMM_SMU_ALM4_9 | ECU Internal

Extra.OBDCode:
P060C-96

Internal Control Module Main Processor Performance

Component Internal Failure
Extra.GeneralRemark:
The module MoXEMM for IFX controller makes a diagnoses of the EMM (Error Management Module) alarms, which are reported by the hardware unit SMU (Safety Management Unit).
The hardware unit SMU is a central component of the hardware safety architecture to manage the behavior of the microcontroller under the presence of hardware faults. The SMU centralizes all the alarm signals related to the different hardware and software−based safety mechanisms.
The SMU unit contains different alarm groups of which the status of each alarm is stored in corresponding status registes. The software modul MoCEMM collects cyclically the context of this status registers and provides these information to MoXEMM.
Extra.TestCondition: Continuously
Extra.FaultDetection: Safety Management Unit (SMU), Alarm Group 4 Failure 9 issued

Name: MSFRD1_1000NoSpark
Title: Misfire Without Spark Ignition In Cylinder 1 For Potential Emission Impact
Description: Misfire Without Spark Ignition In Cylinder 1 For Potential Emission Impact | MSFRD1_1000NoSpark | Ignition Control Module

Extra.OBDCode:
P0301-00

Cylinder 1 Misfire Detected

No Sub Type Information
Extra.GeneralRemark:
Misfire is checked for each single cylinder.
Number of misfire events detected over 1000 engine cycles (2000 rotations) is computed.
Extra.TestCondition:
Monitoring is active If ECU initialized since at least 6.00s while engine isn't running yet, While Engine is not in cranking mode, 6.00s after startup if engine is running, If battery voltage > 10.00V, If battery voltage > 10.00V since at least 2.00s, If ECU is not in afterrun, If Terminal 15 is ON, While Monitor not inhibited by another failure ( Fid_ComCILAddCond2 is intact) and If engine speed > 150.00rpm

- Monitor not inhibited (FId_MSFRD1_1000NoSpark is intact)
- Camshaft signal not defective
Extra.FaultDetection: Misfire event for cylinder 1 detected over an interval of 1000 camshaft rotations > 12.00adm

Description: Misfire Without Spark Ignition In Cylinder 1 For Potential Catalyst Damage | MSFRD1_200NoSpark | Ignition Control Module

Name: rba_SyC_IrrSwOffTrigEngRun_Event
Title: ECU system: Irregular switch off detected at engine running
Description: ECU system: Irregular switch off detected at engine running | rba_SyC_IrrSwOffTrigEngRun_Event | Main Relay

Extra.OBDCode:
P068A-04

ECM/PCM Power Relay De-Energized Performance - Too Early

System Internal Failure
Extra.GeneralRemark:
"System Control for MDG1C" provides an execution control similar to System Control in MEDC17. It provides e.g. the states "Drive" and "PostDive" and has additional features like 5V Undervoltage detection and calculation of the ECU Off Time.
The "Irregular Switch Off Counter" is an instance of an observation counter. The task of it is to observe if the ECU was running all the time since the ECU was switched on till it is switched off.
If the ECU was switched of "irregularly" before end of shutdown was reached (e.g. by supply loss, power−on reset or SoftwareReset while T15 is off) the reset of the counter did not happen. This will lead in next initialization after reading counter from NvM to detect the counter is not zero and an error is set.
Extra.TestCondition: Engine is running
Extra.FaultDetection:
Irregular ECU switch off detected.

ECU was switched off more than 3 times before the condition 'End of Shutdown reached' was fulfilled.

P0685-01

ECM/PCM Power Relay Control Circuit/Open

General Electrical Failure
Extra.GeneralRemark:
The hardware encapsulation of CY320 performs a diagnostic of the sensor supplies and monitors the communication Between processor and voltage supply device CY320.
For reasons of safety the ECM provides 6 independent 5V voltage supplies for the sensors. These sensor supply voltages are monitored to ensure they remain within a given range. This check for voltage limits is done autonomously by the hardware (thresholds not applicable).
Extra.TestCondition: Continuously
Extra.FaultDetection: The sensor supply voltage is monitored by an HW comparator. If the sensor supply voltage lies outside of the switching thresholds, a fault is output. The detection thresholds are defined by the hardware and cannot be calibrated.

Name: ThrVlvHBrgOvrLoad
Title: Throttle Valve Actuator: Over load of H-Bridge
Description: Throttle Valve Actuator: Over load of H-Bridge | ThrVlvHBrgOvrLoad | TVA

Extra.OBDCode:
P2108-19

Throttle Actuator "A" Control Module Performance

Circuit Current Above Threshold
Extra.GeneralRemark:
The Power stage of electric Throttle Valve actuator (H-Bridge) is monitored by Hardware for electric failures. An overload error is not detectable directly in case the wiring length is > 1m and the failure occurs near the actuator. Therefore a plausibility check is made in case a failure "Short circuit to Battery" (SCB) or "Short circuit to Ground" (SCG) is detected. 
Therefore the switch (Low side in case of SCB , High side in case of SCG) is closed. If the Short Circuit failure disappears, it is cleared and the Overload failure activated.
Extra.TestCondition: Monitoring is active If battery voltage > 10.00V and If battery voltage > 10.00V since at least 2.00s
Extra.FaultDetection:
Short Circuit over Load error. 

In case of short-circuit-to-ground error, the High side switches are closed. If there is no more short-circuit-to-ground error then it is detected as short-circuit-over-load error.

In case of short-circuit-to-battery error, low side switches are closed. If there is no more short-circuit-to-battery error then it is detected as short-circuit-over-load error.

If short-circuit overload error is detected, then the pre-existing SCG/SCB error is healed.

Name: TwcEffMon
Title: Three Way Catalyst: Efficiency monitor, ageing detected based on rich/lean variation amplitude
Description: Three Way Catalyst: Efficiency monitor, ageing detected based on rich/lean variation amplitude | TwcEffMon | Catalyst

Extra.OBDCode:
P0420-00

Catalyst System Efficiency Below Threshold Bank 1

No Sub Type Information
Extra.GeneralRemark:
Efficiency of Three Way Catalyst is monitored.
The goal of the strategy is to detect a catalyst ageing, which usually occurs as a loss of storage capacity.
An aged system shows higher rich and lean breakthrough and, therefore, its real behavior has higher variations in the conversion outcome and in the gas composition between the rich and the lean phases, so there is a more noisy LSF signal, but that would remain symmetric around the target.
Extra.TestCondition: Catalyst temperature > 370.00°C, Air fuel control feedback between 0.75adm and  1.25adm, vehicle speed between 0.00km/h and  130.00km/h, post cat lambda filtered between 10.00mV and 1000.00mV, engine speed between 1000.00rpm and 2400.00rpm, lambda upstream in closed loop control, TWC adaption enabled since at least 2.00s, Fraction of storage sites occupied by oxygen inside TWC cell 4 is between 0.00adm and 1.00adm, engine running in steady state and inside OBD enabling running conditions
Extra.FaultDetection: If the standard deviation of the sensor signal  becomes higher than a threshold defined in a map engine speed and volumetric efficiency dependant for at least 15.00adm

Description:
Dif 1 - ASR
Valve, voltage below normal, or shorted to low source

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check for corroded / damaged wiring between the ECU and TCV*.
Measure resistance between TCV GND and TCV. It should be 28 Ohm for 12V system or 128 Ohm for 24V system. (Connector-PIN: X1-4 and X1-5)
Measure insulation resistance of valve and cabling to vehicle GND. Resistance should be > 200 kOhm. If insulation is correct then Clear DTCs. If the failure returns, replace the ECU.
* alternative CRAM: X1-4 is not used, TCV connected to CRAM (port 22 side), resistance 5,2 Ohm for 12V system or 15 Ohm for 24V system. Ground connection of CRAM (port 22 side) is X2-12, shared with PCV_DL_IV.
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description:
Dif 1 - ASR
Valve, voltage above normal, or shorted to high source

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check for corroded / damaged wiring between the ECU and TCV*.
Measure resistance between TCV GND and TCV. It should be 28 Ohm for 12V system or 128 Ohm for 24V system. (Connector-PIN: X1-4 and X1-5)
Measure insulation resistance of valve and cabling to vehicle voltage (UB). Resistance should be > 200 kOhm. Measure insulation resistance of valve and cabling to any other ABS/ASR valve. Resistance should be > 200 kOhm If insulation is correct then Clear DTCs. If the failure returns, replace the ECU.
* alternative CRAM: X1-4 is not used, TCV connected to CRAM (port 22 side), resistance 5,2 Ohm for 12V system or 15 Ohm for 24V system. Ground connection of CRAM (port 22 side) is X2-12, shared with PCV_DL_IV.
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description:
Dif 1 - ASR
Valve, special instructions

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Replace the valve for the correct voltage rating type (12V-24V)
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description:
Dif 1 - ASR
Valve, out of calibration

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check the vehicle documentation for the correct configuration. If necessary reconfigure the ECU.
If vehicle should be without this valve remove connection on the ECU. (Connector-PIN: X1-4* and X1-5 should be empty)
* alternative CRAM: X1-4 is not used. (Connector-PIN: X1-5 should be empty) Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC.

Measure insulation resistance of valve and cabling to vehicle voltage (UB). Resistance should be > 200 kOhm. Measure insulation resistance of valve and cabling to any other ABS/ASR valve. Resistance should be > 200 kOhm If insulation is correct then Clear DTCs. If the failure returns, replace the ECU.
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description:
Brake Light Switch 1, mechanical system not responding or out of
adjustment

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Apply and release the brake pedal.
If the failure is still active, check the wiring of the stop lamp switch input or the stop lamp signal transmitting device (timeout of J1939 CCVS message).
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description: Brake Light Switch 1, data erratic, intermittent or incorrect

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Apply and release service brake:
With service brake released, the stop lamp switch input should be 0V.
With service brake applied, verify system voltage is now present at the stop lamp switch input to the ECU. Check the wiring of the brake signal transmitting device.
Check the wiring of the brake switch input of the ECU or the J1939 message (CCVS).
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description: Wheel Speed Sensor 1, data erratic, intermittent or incorrect

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check the cables and connectors between ECU and wheel-speed sensor for short-circuits and open-circuits. The resistance of the sensor (with wiring) should be 900-2000 Ohm. (Connector-PIN: X2-5 and X2-8)
Check insulation resistance of sensor and cabling to vehicle GND and to UB. Resistance should be >200 kOhm. Check for corroded / damaged wiring or connectors between the ECU and sensor.
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description: SAE SPN text, FMI text - SAE Standard

Extra.WorkshopAction: Workshop Action

Description: Wheel Speed Sensor 1, below normal operational range - most severe level

Extra.WorkshopAction:
The air-gap is too large between the sensor and the tone wheel.
Sensor voltage output is minimally 0.25 VAC at 0.5 revs / sec. (Connector-PIN: X2-5 and X2-8) If signal too small push back the sensor completely to the tone wheel.
Verify proper bearing end-play.
Verify condition and retention of clamping sleeve. Verify condition of sensor head.
Check for corroded / damaged wiring or connectors between the ECU and sensor.
Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC. Verification of the wheel speed signal required by End of Line test or driving of the vehicle. The sensor DTC will remain active until (without clearing DTCs):
After power off-on the ABS ECU, vehicle is driven above 15-20 km/h and the ABS ECU reads good wheel speed data from all sensors.

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check if the sensor mounting is vibration-free.
Check the tone wheel for dirt and metallic particles, for wobble, for pitch error, for the correct number of teeth. Verify condition of sensor head.
Verify proper bearing end-play.
Verify condition and retention of clamping sleeve. Check the mechanical parts of the brake.
Check for corroded / damaged wiring or connectors between the ECU and sensor.
Measure resistance of Sensor and cabling. Resistance should be 900-2000 Ohm. (Connector-PIN: X2-5 and X2-8)
Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC. Verification of the wheel speed signal required by End of Line test or driving of the vehicle. The sensor DTC will remain active until (without clearing DTCs):
After power off-on the ABS ECU, vehicle is driven above 15-20 km/h and the ABS ECU reads good wheel speed data from all sensors.

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check for voltage and ground at pressure sensor wire harness.
Verify wiring between pressure sensor signal and the ECU. The signal line voltage range is 0.5V to 4.5V. Verify there is no continuity between the pressure sensor and power / ground.
If the failure returns, replace the pressure sensor.
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description: Steering Wheel Angle, mechanical system not responding or out of adjustment

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Verify proper installation of the steering angle sensor. Check if correct steering parts are installed.
Check steering parts (steering gearbox, steering rod, steering locks,...) for damage or correct installation.
If all steering parts are ok and correct, check if the steering wheel angle sensor is calibrated in straight line position by checking output using Diagnostics. If necessary, then perform Steering Angle Sensor calibration using Diagnostics.
Check the ABS/ESP dataset for correct value of the parameter. Verify input voltage to sensor connector. The voltage range is 8 to 16 volts. Verify proper wiring between ECU and steering angle sensor by checking the continuity between Sensor CAN Low / High of ECU and SAS wiring connector.
Verify wiring between the Steering Angle Sensor and power/ground. The resistance measurement is open circuit (no continuity). After any repair work on the steering a calibration of the steering wheel angle senor is necessary.
Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC or:
After the fault is detected the ignition should be switched off and on, thus the ECU is reset.
- standstill calibration of YRS is finished
- vehicle speed is greater than 11 km/h
- straight line driving (no strong changes of yaw rate)
- curve driving (stationary, no strong steering angle changes)
The sensors are checked during straight line driving and curve driving.
Reverse checking is only successful if both straight line and curve driving tests are successful. The result of the reverse check is indicated via the VDC Fully Operational info.

Description: SAE SPN text, FMI text - SAE Standard

Extra.WorkshopAction:

Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description: Valve common ground, voltage below normal, or shorted to low source

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check all the valve ground cables if they have a short-cut to vehicle ground.
Measure insulation resistance of solenoid and cabling to vehicle GND. (Connector-PIN: vehicle GND: X1-1, valve grounds depending on configuration: X1-4, X2-3, X2-6, X2-9, X2-12, X3-3, X3-6, X3-9, X4-12)
Resistance should be > 200 kOhm. Verify if the valves are connected.
If insulation is correct then Clear DTCs. If the failure returns, replace the ECU.
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description: Speed Signal Input, mechanical system not responding or out of adjustment

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Wheel speed sensors reversed on an axle (left to right).
Verify proper installation, connection and wiring of sensors and verifying location of sensors on the vehicle.
Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC. Verification of the wheel speed signal required by End of Line test or driving of the vehicle. Curve driving also has to be performed.
The sensor DTC will remain active until (without clearing DTCs):
After power off-on the ABS ECU, vehicle is driven above 15-20 km/h and the ABS ECU reads good wheel speed data from all sensors.

Description: Wheel Speed Sensor 5, data erratic, intermittent or incorrect

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check the cables and connectors between ECU and wheel-speed sensor for short-circuits and open-circuits. The resistance of the sensor (with wiring) should be 900-2000 Ohm. (Connector-PIN: X3-11 and X3-14)
Check insulation resistance of sensor and cabling to vehicle GND and to UB. Resistance should be >200 kOhm. Check for corroded / damaged wiring or connectors between the ECU and sensor.
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Description: Wheel Speed Sensor 5, below normal operational range - most severe level

Extra.WorkshopAction:
The air-gap is too large between the sensor and the tone wheel.
Sensor voltage output is minimally 0.25 VAC at 0.5 revs / sec. (Connector-PIN: X3-11 and X3-14) If signal too small push back the sensor completely to the tone wheel.
Verify proper bearing end-play.
Verify condition and retention of clamping sleeve. Verify condition of sensor head.
Check for corroded / damaged wiring or connectors between the ECU and sensor.
Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC. Verification of the wheel speed signal required by End of Line test or driving of the vehicle. The sensor DTC will remain active until (without clearing DTCs):
After power off-on the ABS ECU, vehicle is driven above 15-20 km/h and the ABS ECU reads good wheel speed data from all sensors.

Description: Wheel Speed Sensor 5, abnormal frequency or pulse width or period

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check if the sensor mounting is vibration-free.
Check the tone wheel for dirt and metallic particles, for wobble, for pitch error, for the correct number of teeth. Verify condition of sensor head.
Verify proper bearing end-play.
Verify condition and retention of clamping sleeve. Check the mechanical parts of the brake.
Check for corroded / damaged wiring or connectors between the ECU and sensor.
Measure resistance of Sensor and cabling. Resistance should be 900-2000 Ohm.(Connector-PIN: X3-11 and X3-14)
Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC. Verification of the wheel speed signal required by End of Line test or driving of the vehicle. The sensor DTC will remain active until (without clearing DTCs):
After power off-on the ABS ECU, vehicle is driven above 15-20 km/h and the ABS ECU reads good wheel speed data from all sensors.

Check the mechanical parts of the brake (dragging, jammed brake).
Check the tone wheel for dirt, wobble/runout or damages (missed or destroyed teeth), which can increase the gap between sensor and tone- wheel or the sensor signal quality.

Description: Wheel Speed Sensor 6, abnormal rate of change

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check if the air-gap is too large between the sensor and the tone wheel. If it too large, push back the sensor completely to the tone wheel. Measure resistance of Sensor and cabling. Resistance should be 900-2000 Ohm. (Connector-PIN: X3-12 and X3-15)
Check the mechanical parts of the brake (dragging, jammed brake).
Check the tone wheel for dirt, wobble/runout or damages (missed or destroyed teeth), which can increase the gap between sensor and tone- wheel or the sensor signal quality.
Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC. Verification of the wheel speed signal required by End of Line test or driving of the vehicle. The sensor DTC will remain active until (without clearing DTCs):
After power off-on the ABS ECU, vehicle is driven above 15-20 km/h and the ABS ECU reads good wheel speed data from all sensors.

Description: Wheel Speed Sensor 6, out of calibration

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check if tire size of all tires is according vehicle specification.
Check C3 Signal calibration, check tachograph for additional fault codes. Check number of teeth on tone wheel on all wheels.
Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC. Verification of the wheel speed signal required by End of Line test or driving of the vehicle. The sensor DTC will remain active until (without clearing DTCs):
After power off-on the ABS ECU, vehicle is driven above 15-20 km/h and the ABS ECU reads good wheel speed data from all sensors.

Description:
Brake Torque Output Axle 1 Left, mechanical system not responding or out of
adjustment

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Check/change faultless brake components at the wheel end, clean/change dirtened wheel end brake parts - pads/discs/drums, tighten/change a leaky piping to brake cylinder, check/change whether comparable tyres are mounted at the affected axle (wear, tyre type, season type, aging), check/change whether identical brake pads/discs/drums are mounted at the affected axle (wear, type, aging), check/correct symmetric load conditions at the affected axle (wheel-wise weighing), check/change faultless vehicle suspension, check/correct track of vehicle. In case of changed components run diagnostic routine reinitializeSelfLearnedParameters.
Verification Procedure:
Clear DTC and perform a test-drive with different braking events, mainly during straight driving.

Description: Yaw Rate, abnormal update rate

Extra.WorkshopAction:
Verify proper wiring between ECU and Yaw-Rate Sensor by checking the continuity between Sensor CAN Low / High of ECU and SAS wiring connector.
Verify wiring between the Yaw-Rate Sensor and power/ground. The resistance measurement is open circuit (no continuity). If the failure returns replace the sensor.
Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.

Verification Procedure: Clear DTC.
